<seg id=1> Thailand Financial Minister Thaksin Going to Japan For Talks On Saving Loans </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (FNA news from Bangkok)Thailand Financial Minister Thaksin departed yesterday for Tokyo to talk about Thailand's share of Japan's saving set for Asian economy in the financial crisis. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> He said that profound discussions would be held during his 4 days visit to Japan but he had no idea how much Japan would give to Thailand. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> "Last night i reported to the Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai the application outlines of the loan. whereas, we are not certain about the amount of the loan for Japan has not informed us of it yet", said xxxx to the media at Bangkok International Airport. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> He also expressed hope to obtain Japnan's generosity and low interest rate in the payoff requirements. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> He said that he would hold seperate meetings with officials from Japan Trade and Industry Ministry, discussing on new measures in aid of reorganization of Thailand's industry and algriculture. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Japan Financial Minister Kiichi Miyazama declared saving set of 30 billion US dollars at the 7-States Group Summit on October, 3. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Japan would allocate 15 billion US dollars to trade and financial field in a short period. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Japan would provide direct financial aid through loans from its imports and exports banks and purchases of Asian bonds. It would also provide Asian countries with Yen loans in aid of development. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> It would also help Asian countries raise funds by guaranteeing bank credits to them and their issue of Asian bonds. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=11> zzzz's saving set is essential to Thailand for it just extended its issue plan of 500 million US dollars of global bonds last month, </seg>
<seg id=12> hoping to use this amount of money to add more circulating capital in it economy, </seg>
<seg id=13> which has been severely stricken by expensive credit cost and global new-rise market. </seg>
</p>
